    </header>

    <!-- MAIN CONTENT -->
    <main class="main">

      <!-- INTRO SECTION -->
      <section class="section">
        <h2 class="section-title">Introduction</h2>
        <p class="body-text">
          Dominant 7th chords are a great next step once you’re comfortable with basic major and minor shapes.
          They’re formed by taking a major chord and adding one extra note called the minor 7th.
          This small change creates a sound that’s bluesy, slightly tense, and full of character.
          You’ll hear dominant 7th chords in blues, rock, jazz, and many classic guitar riffs.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- A7 -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="card">
          <h3 class="card-title">A7</h3>

          <!-- IMAGE: A7 chord diagram -->
          <img class="lesson-image" src="./Assets/Images/A 7.jpg" alt="A7 guitar chord diagram">

          <p class="body-text">
            <strong>Chord tones:</strong> A (root), C♯ (major third), E (perfect fifth), G (minor seventh)
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- D7 -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="card">
          <h3 class="card-title">D7</h3>

          <!-- IMAGE: D7 chord diagram -->
          <img class="lesson-image" src="./Assets/Images/D 7.jpg" alt="D7 guitar chord diagram">

          <p class="body-text">
            <strong>Chord tones:</strong> D (root), F♯ (major third), A (perfect fifth), C (minor seventh)
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- G7 -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="card">
          <h3 class="card-title">G7</h3>

          <!-- IMAGE: G7 chord diagram -->
          <img class="lesson-image" src="./Assets/Images/G 7.jpg" alt="G7 guitar chord diagram">

          <p class="body-text">
            <strong>Chord tones:</strong> G (root), B (major third), D (perfect fifth), F (minor seventh)
          </p>
        </div>
