<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>Learn to Read Guitar Chord Charts</title>

  <link rel="stylesheet" href="./style.css">

  <!-- Google Fonts -->
  <link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.googleapis.com">
  <link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.gstatic.com" crossorigin>
  <link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Special+Elite&family=Merriweather:wght@400;700&family=Montserrat:wght@400;600&display=swap" rel="stylesheet">
</head>

<body>

  <div class="page">

    <!-- HEADER -->
    <header class="header">
      <h1 class="page-title">Learn to Read Guitar Chord Charts</h1>
    </header>

    <!-- MAIN CONTENT -->
    <main class="main">

      <!-- INTRODUCTION -->
      <section class="section">
        <h2 class="section-title">Introduction</h2>
        <p class="body-text">
          Guitar chord charts are simple visual maps that show you where to place your fingers on the fretboard.
          At first, they might look confusing, but once you understand a few basic symbols, they become easy to read.
          This page will walk you through each part of a chord chart step by step, so you can confidently learn new
          chords and start playing real music.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- THE CHORD CHART GRID -->
      <section class="section">
        <h2 class="section-title">The Chord Chart Grid</h2>

        <!-- IMAGE: Blank chord chart grid (no dots, no labels) -->
        <figure class="lesson-figure">
            <img 
                class="lesson-image"
                src="./Assets/Images/Chord Diagram.png"
                alt="empty chord diagram"
            >
            <figcaption class="lesson-caption">
                Blank Chord Diagram
            </figcaption>
        </figure>
    

        <p class="body-text">
          A chord chart is drawn as if you are looking straight at the guitar’s fretboard.
          The vertical lines represent the strings, and the horizontal lines represent the frets.
          The string on the left is the thick low E string, and the string on the right is the thin high E string.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- STRINGS -->
      <section class="section">
        <h2 class="section-title">The Strings</h2>

        <!-- IMAGE: Chord chart with strings labeled (E A D G B e) -->

          <img 
                class="lesson-image"
                src="./Assets/Images/Chord Chart with strings.png"
                alt="chord diagram"
            >
            <figcaption class="lesson-caption">
                Chord Chart with Strings Labelled
            </figcaption>

        <p class="body-text">
          The six vertical lines in a chord chart represent the six strings of the guitar.
          From left to right, they are the low E, A, D, G, B, and high E strings.
          Even though the high E string is also called E, it is thinner and higher in pitch.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- FRETS -->
      <section class="section">
        <h2 class="section-title">The Frets</h2>

        <!-- IMAGE: Chord chart showing fret numbers (1, 2, 3) -->
           <img 
                class="lesson-image"
                src="./Assets/Images/Chord Chart with strings.png"
                alt="chord diagram"
            >
            <figcaption class="lesson-caption">
                Chord Chart with Frets Labelled
            </figcaption>

        <p class="body-text">
          The horizontal lines represent the frets.
          The top line is usually the nut of the guitar, and the spaces between the lines are the frets.
          When you place your finger on a fret, press just behind the metal bar, not directly on top of it.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- FINGER PLACEMENT -->
      <section class="section">
        <h2 class="section-title">Finger Placement Dots</h2>

        <!-- IMAGE: Simple chord diagram (A major or C major) -->
           <img 
                class="lesson-image"
                src="./Assets/Images/A Major.jpg"
                alt="A Major Chord"
            >
            <figcaption class="lesson-caption">
                A Major Chord
            </figcaption>

        <p class="body-text">
          The filled-in dots show where to place your fingers.
          Each dot tells you which string to press and on which fret.
          If more than one dot appears on the same fret, it means you are pressing multiple strings at once.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- OPEN & MUTED STRINGS -->
      <section class="section">
        <h2 class="section-title">Open and Muted Strings</h2>

        <!-- IMAGE: Chord chart with O (open) and X (muted) symbols -->
           <img 
                class="lesson-image"
                src="./Assets/Images/C Major.jpg"
                alt="C Major Chord"
            >
            <figcaption class="lesson-caption">
                C Major Chord
            </figcaption>

        <p class="body-text">
          Symbols above the chord chart tell you how each string should be played.
          An “O” means play the string open without pressing it down.
          An “X” means do not play that string at all.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- FULL EXAMPLE -->
      <section class="section">
        <h2 class="section-title">Reading a Full Chord Chart</h2>

        <!-- IMAGE: Fully labeled chord chart (A major recommended) -->
          <img 
                class="lesson-image"
                src="./Assets/Images/A Major.jpg"
                alt="A Major Chord"
            >
            <figcaption class="lesson-caption">
                A Major Chord
            </figcaption>

           

        <p class="body-text">
          When you put all of these elements together, a chord chart gives you everything you need to know
          to play a chord: which strings to play, where to place your fingers, and which strings to avoid.
          With a little practice, reading chord charts becomes second nature.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- WHAT'S NEXT -->
      <section class="section">
        <h2 class="section-title">What’s Next?</h2>

        <p class="body-text">
          Now that you know how to read chord charts, you’re ready to start learning your first chords.
          In the next sections, we’ll explore major, minor, and 7th chords and show you how to use them in real music.
        </p>

        <!-- OPTIONAL: Button linking to Major Chords page -->

         <a href="major.html" class="button button--primary">
            Next Lesson: Major Chords →
        </a>

      </section>

    </main>

  </div>

</body>
</html>

