<body>

  <div class="page">

    <!-- HEADER -->
    <header class="header">
      <h1 class="page-title">Minor Chords</h1>
    </header>

    <!-- MAIN CONTENT -->
    <main class="main">

      <!-- INTRO SECTION -->
      <section class="section">
        <h2 class="section-title">Introduction</h2>
        <p class="body-text">
          Minor chords have a darker, more emotional sound compared to major chords.
          They’re created by changing just one note in a major chord: the major third becomes a minor third.
          This small change gives minor chords their sad, moody character.
          In this section, you’ll learn the essential open-position minor chord shapes.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- A MINOR -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="card">
          <h3 class="card-title">A Minor</h3>

          <!-- IMAGE: A Minor chord diagram -->
          <img class="lesson-image" src="./Assets/Images/A Minor.jpg" alt="A minor guitar chord diagram">

          <p class="body-text">
            <strong>Chord tones:</strong> A (root), C (minor third), E (perfect fifth)
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- D MINOR -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="card">
          <h3 class="card-title">D Minor</h3>

          <!-- IMAGE: D Minor chord diagram -->
          <img class="lesson-image" src="./Assets/Images/D Minor.jpg" alt="D minor guitar chord diagram">

          <p class="body-text">
            <strong>Chord tones:</strong> D (root), F (minor third), A (perfect fifth)
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- E MINOR -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="card">
